<doc id="68666" wikidata="Q4751403" url="?curid=68666" title="Ananiah">
<text>Ananiah, in the Bible, is a town in the tribe of Benjamin between Nob and Hazor (modern Tell el-Qedah) (). It is one of the localities inhabited by the tribe of Benjamin after the return from the Babylonian Exile. Ananiah, whose name means &quot;protected by God,&quot; was identified by the 19th century French traveler V. Guérin, author of &quot;Description de La Jude&#x27;e&quot;, with the present-day Beit Hanina, located 3 miles north of Jerusalem. Edward Robinson concurred, but W.F. Albright maintained that Ananiah is the village of al-Eizariya east of Jerusalem. Some modern scholars also identify Ananiah with al-Eizariya.

